  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Parents transferring a home to a child, siblings restructuring ownership after an inheritance, or a partner putting the other on title are all common scenarios in Brisbane's inner east. The emotional logic is obvious. The legal and tax mechanics are less so. Gifting property in Queensland is treated, for most tax and duty purposes, the same as a sale at market value. Understanding that principle up front avoids the most expensive surprises.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how a gift transfer actually works in Queensland, the duty and capital gains tax consequences for both sides, and the practical steps that keep the transaction clean. It does not replace advice from a solicitor or accountant, and anyone considering a gift should get both before signing anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'gifting' actually means</h2>
      <p>A gift, in property terms, is a transfer of ownership for no consideration. No purchase price. No loan arrangement. No informal promise of future payment. The transfer is documented on a standard Queensland land title transfer form, signed by both parties, and lodged with Titles Queensland along with the relevant supporting documents. Once registered, the recipient becomes the legal owner exactly as if they had bought the property.</p>

      <p>People sometimes confuse gifting with selling below market value, for example a parent selling a home to a child for $1. These are treated differently by the Queensland Revenue Office and by the Australian Taxation Office, but the practical outcome is similar because both transactions are assessed against the property's market value, not the amount stated on the contract. If you are considering a sale at a nominal price rather than a full gift, read our companion article on selling below market value to family.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Transfer duty still applies</h2>
      <p>This is the single most misunderstood point. Even when a property is gifted and no money changes hands, transfer duty (formerly stamp duty) is still payable. The Queensland Revenue Office assesses duty on the market value of the property at the date of transfer, based on a sworn valuation. The recipient of the gift pays the duty.</p>

      <p>For a Brisbane inner-east property worth $1.4 million, transfer duty at current rates is a substantial five-figure liability. A family gifting the Morningside family home to an adult child is asking that child to find roughly $55,000 to $60,000 in duty before the transfer can be registered. That is not something most recipients can absorb without planning. The duty must be paid within 30 days of signing the transfer, and registration is blocked until it is.</p>

      <p>There is a narrow exception for transfers between spouses or de facto partners of their principal place of residence, where duty may be reduced or exempted under section 151 of the Duties Act 2001 (Qld). That concession does not apply to parent-to-child gifts, sibling transfers, or transfers of investment property. If you are relying on an exception, have your solicitor confirm it in writing before you proceed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax for the person giving</h2>
      <p>The second big trap is capital gains tax. For CGT purposes, gifting a property is treated as a disposal at market value. The giver is deemed to have sold the property at its current market value on the date of transfer, and a capital gain (or loss) is calculated against their original cost base.</p>

      <p>If the property has been the giver's main residence throughout the ownership period, the main residence exemption will generally apply and the capital gain is not taxable. This is why gifting the family home often has no CGT consequence for the parent. But if the property has been rented out at any point, used to generate income, or held as an investment, the main residence exemption is reduced or lost altogether, and the giver faces a CGT bill calculated against an assessed market value they never actually received.</p>

      <p>This matters most for parents gifting a former home that was rented out after they moved. The capital gain accrues from the date the property stopped being the main residence (or from the date it was first rented under the six-year rule), and the gift crystallises that liability. A $400,000 capital gain on a property gifted at retirement can produce a CGT bill of $90,000 or more, due on the giver's tax return for the year of transfer. Plan for it in advance or the gift becomes a financial shock at exactly the point in life where cash flow is tightest.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The recipient's new cost base</h2>
      <p>When a recipient receives a gifted property, their cost base for future CGT purposes is the market value at the date of transfer, not what the giver originally paid. This is usually a favourable outcome: the built-up capital gain from the giver's ownership period is either covered by the main residence exemption or taxed in the giver's hands, and the recipient starts fresh.</p>

      <p>If the recipient then sells the property themselves within a few years, the capital gain they pay tax on is calculated from the transfer-date value, not from what the parents paid in 1998. That is often helpful. What it also means is that the recipient does not inherit the giver's cost base, and any pre-existing cost base advantages (for example, a very low original purchase price) are effectively reset at the point of gift.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Existing mortgages and encumbrances</h2>
      <p>A property with an existing mortgage cannot simply be gifted on. The mortgage must be discharged before or at settlement of the transfer, or the recipient must formally assume the loan, which typically requires the lender's approval and a new credit assessment in the recipient's name. Most lenders will not permit an assumption of an existing loan, and the usual path is to refinance or pay out the loan at the point of transfer.</p>

      <p>If the giver is paying out the loan from their own funds to clean the title before gifting, that is also relevant to the recipient's duty calculation. The duty is assessed on the full market value, not on the equity portion. Caveats, easements, or body corporate issues also need to be resolved or formally disclosed before the transfer is registered.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Social security and pension implications</h2>
      <p>If the giver is receiving a Centrelink pension or benefit, gifting a property triggers the 'deprivation' rules. Centrelink treats assets given away above $10,000 in a single year (or $30,000 over five years) as still belonging to the giver for asset test purposes for five years from the date of transfer. A $1.4 million gifted property is well above these thresholds and will be assessed as part of the giver's assets for five years, which can significantly affect pension eligibility.</p>

      <p>This catches many retiring parents by surprise. The intention is usually to simplify estate arrangements and help an adult child onto the property ladder. The Centrelink consequence is a reduced or cancelled pension for five years, on top of any CGT exposure and the recipient's duty bill. Services Australia should be consulted before the transfer, not after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Family Law considerations</h2>
      <p>Once a property is transferred to a child or family member, it becomes their asset for family law purposes. If the recipient is married or in a de facto relationship and that relationship later ends, the gifted property is typically part of the matrimonial property pool and subject to division. This is an uncomfortable topic but a real one, and parents making substantial gifts often use tools like binding financial agreements, protective trusts, or a loan structure rather than an outright gift, specifically to preserve the asset in the family.</p>

      <p>The choice between an outright gift and a structured arrangement is not something to decide on the basis of a family conversation alone. A family lawyer can outline the realistic protections available and the trade-offs of each. The cost of that advice is modest compared to the consequences of getting the structure wrong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The transfer process, step by step</h2>
      <p>Once the decision to proceed has been made and advice has been obtained, the mechanical transfer itself is straightforward. A solicitor or conveyancer prepares a transfer document and the supporting forms required by Titles Queensland. A market valuation is obtained, either from a registered valuer or by using the Queensland Revenue Office's prescribed method, to substantiate the duty assessment.</p>

      <p>Both parties sign the transfer. The QRO assesses duty, the recipient pays it, and any existing mortgage is discharged (or a new one registered in the recipient's name). The transfer is then lodged with Titles Queensland, and upon registration the title is issued in the recipient's name. Start to finish, allow six to twelve weeks for a clean gift transfer, longer if a loan refinance or a caveat needs to be resolved first.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Alternatives worth considering</h2>
      <p>An outright gift is not always the best tool for the job. Parents wanting to help a child buy a home often achieve the same outcome with less tax friction through other structures. A loan with documented terms (forgivable or not) keeps the title clear and avoids triggering the giver's CGT. Acting as a guarantor on the child's mortgage puts no asset into the child's name. A joint purchase, with parents retaining a percentage share, splits both the duty and any later capital gain.</p>

      <p>For intergenerational wealth planning, a testamentary trust created in a will can transfer property to children on the parents' death, generally with more favourable tax treatment than a lifetime gift. An experienced estate planning solicitor will compare the options against your specific goals and family situation rather than assuming an outright gift is the right answer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The conversation to have first</h2>
      <p>Before any paperwork starts, have the full conversation with everyone affected. The recipient needs to understand they are responsible for the duty bill, the future rates and insurance, and any existing maintenance or debt on the property. The giver needs to be clear-eyed about the CGT position, the Centrelink implications, and the family law exposure. Other children or beneficiaries should know what is happening so the gift does not become a source of family dispute later.</p>

      <p>Gifting property can be a genuinely generous and effective way to help the next generation. Done without the right advice, it can also produce tax bills, benefit losses, and family conflict that outweigh the benefit. Treat it as a planned transaction, not a spontaneous gesture, and the outcome is almost always better.</p>

